{"cursor":"9653","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nThe 'zucchetto' (;\n; [http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/zucchetto?q=zucchetto\nOxford Dictionary] Italian: \"small [[gourd]]\", from zucca,\n\"[[pumpkin]]\", Compare [[zucchini]], of related origin.\nfiguratively referred to the human head\n[http://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/zucchetto/ Dizionario Treccani] ) is a\nsmall, hemispherical, form-fitting ecclesiastical skullcap, worn by clerics of\nthe Roman Catholic Church and also used by the higher clergy in Anglicanism as\nwell as in the Eastern Orthodox Church tradition. The plural is zucchetti, and\nit is also known by the names 'pilus', 'pilos', 'pileus', 'pileolus' (pileolo),\n'subbiretum', 'submitrale', 'soli deo' (\"solideo\"), 'berettino', 'calotte'\n(\"calotta\").\n","linknr":239,"url":"Zucchetto","recorded":1362566612,"links":39,"instances":["color","liturgy","liturgy","color","cap","catholicism","hat"],"pdf":["http://www.hatsuk.com/skullcaps.pdf"],"categories":["Religious headwear","Papal vestments","Roman Catholic vestments","Anglican vestments","Lutheran vestments","History of clothing","History of clothing (Europe)","History of clothing (Western fashion)","History of fashion"],"headings":["History","Construction and design","Usage","Notes and references","See also","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Cardinal_zucchetto_2003_modified_2008-15-08.jpg/220px-Cardinal_zucchetto_2003_modified_2008-15-08.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Gamarelli_Papal_zucchetto20050412.jpg/220px-Gamarelli_Papal_zucchetto20050412.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Wikisource-logo.svg/38px-Wikisource-logo.svg.